      <h1>Coalitions</h1>
      <p class="page-header__lead">
        Community coalitions, the 12-sector model, and how groups organize
        prevention work locally — applied to gambling, where the model is
        borrowed from substance misuse and the ethical tensions are real.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container prose">
      <h2>What a community coalition is</h2>
      <p>
        A community coalition is, in CADCA's framing, a formal but voluntary
        arrangement in which separate groups or sectors of a community keep
        their own identities and still agree to work together toward a shared
        goal — historically a safe, healthy, drug-free community (CADCA,
        <em>Handbook for Community Anti-Drug Coalitions</em>, 2019). Read
        that definition with gambling in mind and the only thing that
        changes is the goal: a community in which gambling is engaged with
        as a known-risk activity rather than a hidden one, and in which
        problems are identified and addressed early.
      </p>
      <p>
        The most important distinction for a prevention professional is the
        one between a <strong>coalition</strong> and a <strong>program</strong>.
        CADCA frames it directly: coalitions measure success by
        community-level indicators and outcomes, address multiple causes of
        a problem, and diffuse the work across many members with staff
        coordinating; programs measure change in the individuals they
        directly serve, focus on a single strategy (a class, a curriculum,
        a support group), and are led by program staff (CADCA, 2019). A
        coalition is therefore <em>not</em> a prevention program and
        <em>not</em> a direct-service agency. It is the connective tissue
        that lets many programs, agencies, and residents push in the same
        direction on a shared problem.
      </p>
      <p>
        This distinction matters more for gambling than for almost any
        other behavioral-health issue, because gambling-specific
        <em>programs</em> are sparse. Most communities have no
        gambling-prevention curriculum, no gambling counselor, and no
        gambling-specific data. A coalition is a way to build
        population-level capacity where individual-level capacity does not
        yet exist.
      </p>

      <h2>Why the coalition model fits gambling prevention</h2>
      <p>
        Gambling-related harm is produced largely by <strong>community and
        environmental conditions</strong>, not solely by individual choices:
        the density and accessibility of gambling opportunities, the legal
        and regulatory environment, marketing and advertising saturation,
        social norms about betting (especially around sports), and the
        availability — or absence — of screening, help, and financial
        counseling. These are precisely the kinds of conditions that
        coalitions are built to change. A single program reaches the
        individuals in front of it; a coalition can move the conditions
        that put a whole population at risk.
      </p>
      <p>
        The structural change in the U.S. gambling environment makes this
        urgent. The rapid spread of legalized sports betting and the move
        of gambling onto smartphones have expanded exposure dramatically. As
        one coalition leader has put it, the phone in someone's pocket can
        turn losing hundreds or thousands of dollars into a matter of
        seconds (CADCA, <em>The Problem Gambling Coalition of Southwest
        Ohio</em>, 2024). When risk is being driven by environmental change
        at the population scale, a population-scale, multi-sector response
        is the appropriate match.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Honest note on the evidence base.</strong> The strong,
        peer-reviewed effectiveness evidence for the coalition model comes
        from substance misuse — most notably the Drug-Free Communities
        national evaluation, which documented reductions in youth alcohol,
        tobacco, and marijuana use in DFC-funded communities (CADCA, 2019).
        There is not yet a comparably mature outcome literature for
        <em>gambling</em> coalitions. What exists today is (a) a robust,
        transferable model, (b) early national investment to adapt it (NCPG,
        2024; CADCA / Oregon Health Authority, 2025), and (c) a growing set
        of real-world examples. Practitioners should treat the coalition
        model as a well-validated <em>vehicle</em> being applied to a newer
        <em>destination</em>, and should build evaluation in from the start
        rather than assume substance-misuse outcomes will transfer
        automatically.
      </p>

      <h2>CADCA's framework and the Seven Strategies for Community Change</h2>
      <p>
        CADCA — Community Anti-Drug Coalitions of America — is the largest
        membership and training organization for community coalitions in
        the United States, and its National Coalition Institute supplies
        the field's most widely used coalition framework (CADCA, 2019).
        CADCA's framework nests inside SAMHSA's <a
        href="/understand-prevention/strategic-prevention-framework">Strategic
        Prevention Framework</a> (assessment, capacity, planning,
        implementation, evaluation, plus cultural competence and
        sustainability), so a coalition's work is data-driven and
        outcome-oriented rather than activity-driven.
      </p>
      <p>
        The operational heart of the framework — and the part most directly
        useful to a gambling coalition planning its action steps — is the
        <strong>Seven Strategies for Community Change</strong>. These are
        the seven types of action a coalition can take to move
        community-level conditions, ranging from individually focused to
        environmentally focused (CADCA National Coalition Institute,
        <em>Defining the Seven Strategies for Community Change</em>).
      </p>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th scope="col">#</th>
              <th scope="col">Strategy (CADCA)</th>
              <th scope="col">What it means</th>
              <th scope="col">Gambling-prevention example</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>1</td>
              <td><strong>Providing Information</strong></td>
              <td>Educational presentations, data dissemination, public communications</td>
              <td>A coalition runs a Problem Gambling Awareness Month campaign and shares local helpline data and "gambling is not a risk-free activity" messaging.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>2</td>
              <td><strong>Enhancing Skills</strong></td>
              <td>Training, technical assistance, curriculum development to build capacity</td>
              <td>Train school counselors and pediatricians to screen for youth gambling; build a prevention specialist's gambling competency.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>3</td>
              <td><strong>Providing Support</strong></td>
              <td>Alternative activities, mentoring, referral, support groups</td>
              <td>Stand up youth alternative activities and clear referral pathways to gambling treatment and Gamblers Anonymous.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>4</td>
              <td><strong>Enhancing Access / Reducing Barriers</strong></td>
              <td>Improving systems so people can use services</td>
              <td>Make screening, financial counseling, and help routes easier to reach and culturally and linguistically accessible.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>5</td>
              <td><strong>Changing Consequences</strong></td>
              <td>Altering the incentives/disincentives around a behavior</td>
              <td>Support enforcement of underage-gambling penalties and incentives for venues that adopt responsible-gambling practices.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>6</td>
              <td><strong>Physical Design</strong></td>
              <td>Changing the physical/structural environment</td>
              <td>Address signage, ATM placement near gambling, self-exclusion infrastructure, and outlet/access design.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>7</td>
              <td><strong>Modifying / Changing Policies</strong></td>
              <td>Formal change in rules, by-laws, or laws</td>
              <td>Advance advertising restrictions, age verification, deposit/loss limits, or earmarked prevention funding from gambling revenue.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>
        Strategies 5–7 are <em>environmental</em> — the ones that produce
        durable, population-level change — and they are exactly where
        gambling prevention has the most unworked ground (advertising,
        access, age verification, dedicated funding). They are also where
        the coalition's multi-sector composition becomes essential, because
        no single agency can move a policy or a built environment alone.
      </p>
      <p class="note">
        <strong>Source caution.</strong> The Seven Strategies were authored
        by CADCA's National Coalition Institute for substance-misuse
        prevention. The gambling examples in the table above are
        <em>applications by analogy</em> offered for this page; they are
        consistent with how the field is adapting the framework (NCPG, 2024;
        CADCA / Oregon Health Authority, 2025), but the strategy definitions
        themselves come from the substance-misuse source.
      </p>

      <h2>Stages of coalition development</h2>
      <p>
        Coalitions are not founded fully formed; they develop. A practitioner
        should expect to move through formation (recruiting a core group
        and key sectors, agreeing on a shared vision and mission),
        assessment and planning (collecting local data on the problem,
        resources, and readiness, then building a data-driven strategic and
        action plan), implementation (carrying out the chosen strategies
        across sectors), and maintenance/institutionalization (sustaining
        the work, refreshing membership, embedding the coalition as the
        community's "go-to" body on the issue) (CADCA, 2019; Community Tool
        Box, <em>Coalition Building I &amp; II</em>).
      </p>
      <p>
        The Community Tool Box treats this explicitly as two phases —
        <strong>starting a coalition</strong> and <strong>maintaining a
        coalition</strong> — and emphasizes that the maintenance phase
        (keeping members engaged, managing conflict, renewing purpose) is
        where many coalitions falter.
      </p>
      <p>
        For gambling specifically, almost every coalition is
        <strong>early-stage</strong>. The Problem Gambling Coalition of
        Southwest Ohio, for example, formed in the 2020s in direct response
        to legalized sports betting and is still building the local
        research, training, and workforce base (CADCA, <em>Southwest
        Ohio</em>, 2024). The practical implication: gambling coalitions
        should not rush to environmental policy work before they have done
        the assessment, capacity-building, and readiness work that earlier
        stages require.
      </p>

      <h2>The sectors of the community to engage</h2>
      <p>
        To change conditions across an entire community, a coalition must
        include the sectors that touch the problem. CADCA's framework —
        mirrored by the Drug-Free Communities grant requirement of
        <strong>at least 12 community sectors</strong> — names sectors
        including: youth; parents; businesses; media; schools (elementary
        and secondary education); youth-serving organizations; law
        enforcement; faith/fraternal organizations; civic and volunteer
        groups; healthcare professionals; government; and others involved
        in prevention, treatment, or recovery (CADCA, 2019). CADCA also
        stresses including not only "movers and shakers" but grassroots
        residents with strong neighborhood ties.
      </p>
      <p>
        For a gambling coalition, the standard sectors carry over but
        several take on <strong>gambling-specific roles</strong>, and a few
        sectors are distinctive to gambling:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Schools, youth-serving organizations, and youth athletics</strong>
          — sports betting normalizes wagering among young people; coaches,
          athletic departments, and youth sports leagues are front-line
          sectors (NCPG, 2024).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Healthcare and behavioral-health treatment providers</strong>
          — including the (often small) pool of gambling-credentialed
          counselors and the substance-use and mental-health workforce that
          must learn to screen for co-occurring gambling problems.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Financial counseling and consumer-credit services</strong>
          — a sector largely absent from substance-misuse coalitions but
          central to gambling, where harm is heavily financial.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Faith communities</strong> — natural partners for
          non-stigmatizing outreach and support.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Higher education</strong> — colleges are a high-risk
          setting; campus health and student-affairs offices are key
          (reflected in multiple NCPG Agility Grant campus projects; NCPG,
          2024).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Gaming regulators, state lottery, and (with care)
          operators</strong> — these are the sectors with no clean analogue
          in substance-misuse coalitions and the source of the field's
          central ethical tension (see "The industry-funding tension,"
          below).
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Engaging regulators and lottery agencies brings real value — data,
        regulatory levers, and reach — but it also brings conflict-of-interest
        considerations that must be managed deliberately.
      </p>

      <h2>Community readiness: meeting the community where it is</h2>
      <p>
        Before a coalition selects strategies, it should assess how ready
        the community actually is to act. The <strong>Tri-Ethnic Community
        Readiness Model</strong> (Colorado State University's Tri-Ethnic
        Center for Prevention Research) is the field standard. It assesses
        readiness across dimensions including community knowledge of the
        issue, knowledge of existing efforts, leadership, community
        climate, and resources, and it places a community on a
        <strong>nine-stage continuum</strong>: (1) no awareness, (2)
        denial/resistance, (3) vague awareness, (4) preplanning, (5)
        preparation, (6) initiation, (7) stabilization, (8)
        confirmation/expansion, and (9) high level of community ownership
        (Tri-Ethnic Center for Prevention Research, <em>Community Readiness
        Handbook</em>; Community Tool Box, <em>Community Readiness</em>).
      </p>
      <p>
        The model's core teaching is to <strong>match the intervention to
        the stage</strong> — efforts that outrun a community's readiness
        tend to fail. For gambling, readiness is usually <em>low</em>: many
        communities sit at no awareness, denial/resistance, or vague
        awareness, often because gambling is socially accepted, locally
        taxed, or seen as harmless entertainment. The practical lesson is
        that early gambling coalition work should frequently emphasize
        Strategy 1 (Providing Information) and readiness-building — raising
        awareness that gambling is not a risk-free activity — <em>before</em>
        attempting policy or environmental change. Connecticut's Regional
        Gambling Awareness Teams explicitly include assessing community
        awareness and readiness as part of their charge (CT DMHAS, n.d.).
      </p>

      <h2>Coalition functioning and the logic of collaboration</h2>
      <p>
        A coalition's value comes from coordinated, <em>mutually
        reinforcing</em> action — not from a single organization working
        harder. The <strong>collective impact</strong> framework (Kania
        &amp; Kramer, <em>Stanford Social Innovation Review</em>, 2011)
        names the five conditions that distinguish effective cross-sector
        collaboration from a loose committee:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>a <strong>common agenda</strong> (shared understanding of the
          problem and a joint approach);</li>
        <li><strong>shared measurement</strong> (everyone tracking the same
          indicators the same way);</li>
        <li><strong>mutually reinforcing activities</strong> (each sector
          doing what it does best, coordinated);</li>
        <li><strong>continuous communication</strong> (sustained,
          trust-building contact); and</li>
        <li>a <strong>backbone organization</strong> (dedicated
          staff/infrastructure to coordinate the whole).</li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        For gambling, the <strong>shared-measurement</strong> condition is
        the hardest and the most important. Gambling lacks the surveillance
        infrastructure that substance misuse enjoys — CADCA itself has
        called for adding gambling questions to NIDA's <em>Monitoring the
        Future</em> and to the CDC's Youth Risk Behavior Surveillance System
        precisely because current systems give communities little to
        measure (Problem Gambling Toolkit, <em>CADCA Recommendations</em>,
        n.d.). A coalition that agrees up front on what it will count —
        local helpline contacts, screening rates, youth exposure,
        advertising volume — partly compensates for the missing national
        data. The <strong>backbone</strong> condition is equally critical:
        a diffuse, low-readiness issue like gambling needs a dedicated
        coordinating body to keep partners aligned over time. Connecticut's
        RBHAO / Regional Gambling Awareness Team structure functions as
        that backbone at a regional scale (CT DMHAS, n.d.).
      </p>

      <h2>Integrating gambling into an existing coalition vs. building a standalone gambling coalition</h2>
      <p>
        This is a live, practical decision for the PG field, and both
        paths are in use.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Integrating gambling into an existing substance-misuse
        coalition</strong> leverages infrastructure that already exists: an
        established backbone, engaged sectors, community trust, data
        systems, and the gambling–substance co-occurrence that makes the
        addition logical. CADCA's own recommendation that <em>all</em>
        substance-use prevention survey instruments include co-occurring-disorder
        (including gambling) questions reflects this integration logic
        (Problem Gambling Toolkit, n.d.). The risk is that gambling becomes
        a perpetual afterthought to better-funded substance work.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Building a standalone gambling coalition</strong> gives the
        issue undivided focus, a dedicated identity, and the ability to
        recruit gambling-specific sectors (regulators, lottery, financial
        counseling) that a substance coalition might not prioritize. The
        Problem Gambling Coalition of Southwest Ohio is a working example,
        built around a clear gambling mission and a university partnership
        that produces gambling-credentialed prevention specialists (CADCA,
        <em>Southwest Ohio</em>, 2024). The risk is starting from zero on
        infrastructure, funding, and community trust.
      </p>
      <p>
        There is no single correct answer. A reasonable rule of thumb: in
        low-readiness communities with a strong existing coalition,
        <strong>integration</strong> is usually the faster, more sustainable
        path; where gambling-specific sectors and a dedicated identity are
        decisive — for example near major gaming operations or a partnering
        university — a <strong>standalone</strong> coalition can be worth
        the heavier lift. Many states are pursuing a hybrid: a state or
        regional backbone (e.g., Connecticut's Regional Gambling Awareness
        Teams) that supports gambling work embedded in many local
        coalitions (CT DMHAS, n.d.).
      </p>

      <h2>The industry-funding and conflict-of-interest tension</h2>
      <p>
        This is the defining ethical difference between a gambling coalition
        and a substance-misuse coalition, and it deserves to be named
        plainly rather than avoided.
      </p>
      <p>
        Gambling prevention is chronically underfunded — public funding for
        problem-gambling services is a small fraction of what substance use
        receives — which creates real pressure to accept funding or
        participation from the gaming industry (casinos, lottery,
        sportsbooks, online operators). At the same time, the gambling
        research and prevention literature documents that funding from
        parties with a financial stake in gambling can bias which questions
        get asked, how studies are designed, and how findings are
        disseminated (Roberts et al., <em>Addiction</em>, 2025; Cassidy et
        al., PMC). The same dynamic applies to prevention: an operator at
        the coalition table, or operator money in the coalition budget,
        can quietly steer the agenda toward "responsible gambling"
        messaging and away from the environmental and policy strategies
        (advertising limits, access restrictions, deposit limits) that the
        Seven Strategies identify as most effective.
      </p>
      <p>
        This does not mean industry actors can never be engaged —
        regulators, lottery agencies, and even operators hold data and
        levers a coalition may need, and the Southwest Ohio coalition
        reports productively collaborating with venues (CADCA, 2024). It
        means a gambling coalition should decide its boundaries
        <strong>deliberately and in writing</strong> before the question
        is urgent. Practical safeguards drawn from the research-integrity
        literature include: keeping the coalition's mission and agenda
        independent of any funder; written conflict-of-interest and
        gift-acceptance policies; transparency about all funding sources;
        preferring arm's-length funding mechanisms (e.g., regulatory
        settlements or earmarked public funds rather than direct operator
        gifts); and ensuring that people with lived experience of gambling
        harm have a genuine voice (Roberts et al., 2025). NCPG itself
        models neutrality on legalized gambling while focusing squarely on
        reducing harm (NCPG, 2024) — a useful posture for a coalition to
        emulate.
      </p>

      <h2>Sustainability and funding</h2>
      <p>
        Sustainability is one of SAMHSA's Strategic Prevention Framework
        elements for a reason: a coalition that cannot sustain itself
        cannot produce the long-term, population-level change that
        justifies the model (CADCA, 2019). For substance misuse, the DFC
        program provides a relatively stable federal funding base;
        <strong>gambling prevention has no equivalent</strong>. The largest
        dedicated national stream to date is NCPG's Agility Grants — the
        <em>first</em> national initiative to fund problem-gambling
        prevention, which had invested over $1 million across multiple
        rounds as of late 2024, supported in part by industry-adjacent
        partners (NCPG, 2024). State funding (often a small set-aside from
        gambling revenue, as in Connecticut and Ohio) is the other main
        source, and it varies widely by state.
      </p>
      <p>
        The sustainability implication for a gambling coalition is
        concrete: diversify funding early, document outcomes to make the
        case for continued state support, and treat <strong>integration
        with a funded substance-misuse coalition</strong> as a legitimate
        sustainability strategy in its own right — borrowing the DFC
        infrastructure rather than building a parallel one from scratch.
      </p>

      <h2>A note on language</h2>
      <p>
        Use <strong>person-first, non-stigmatizing language</strong> — "a
        person experiencing a gambling problem," not "a gambler" or "an
        addict" — and <strong>spectrum framing</strong> that recognizes
        gambling involvement ranges from no risk to gambling disorder.
        Coalition messaging should be calm and factual: "gambling is not a
        risk-free activity" and "help is available" do the work without
        alarmism (cf. CT DMHAS prevention messages, n.d.).
      </p>

